ish to green, and verify the count matches.\n\nActually, I need to reconsider how the management API works—it doesn't guarantee order or which specific messages get returned when peeking. Since the messages have IDs in their payload, I should track which ones I've already seen and published to avoid confusion. For this migration where duplicates are acceptable, I can create a continuous job that keeps pulling from blue and pushing to green until no new messages appear, ensuring all the initial 50 messages plus any new arrivals make it across.\n\nI'm thinking through what \"cut application traffic to green\" actually means—whether it's redirecting the producer to publish directly to green or updating routing rules. The curl-test pod in the target namespace might be the consumer that validates the migration worked.\n\nLet me start building the migration job first. I'm writing a Kubernetes Job that uses Python to connect to the RabbitMQ management API, read all messages from the blue queue with requeue enabled, and write them to the green queue until all message IDs are transferred.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1987,"cache_read_input_tokens":43998,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1987},"output_tokens":30,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"972f2e5d-1f65-49de-bc8b-cfff6a704196","uuid":"55b35ff6-545c-4470-8050-76b1a77673e1","request_id":"req_011CbxV2hMNtMt6jRCXNvvCr"}
